.\" whodid.1 — manual page for the whodid file-system activity monitor
.\" Process this file with: groff -man -Tutf8 whodid.1 | less
.TH WHODID 1 "April 2026" "whodid 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NAME
whodid \- real-time file-system activity monitor (PID + process per event)
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B whodid
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.I path
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B whodid
monitors file-system activity under
.I path
in real time using the Linux
.BR fanotify (7)
kernel API.
For every file-system event it reports the timestamp, the PID of the
responsible process, the full executable path of that process, the type of
event, and the absolute path of the affected file — all on a single line
ready for
.BR grep (1)
or
.BR awk (1)
post-processing.
.PP
Unlike
.BR lsof (8),
which is a momentary snapshot that misses fast open/close cycles, and unlike
.BR inotifywait (1),
which reports that a file changed but cannot identify the responsible process,
.B whodid
intercepts events at the kernel level and always delivers the originating PID.
It requires no daemon, no rule-file, and no configuration: a single
.B sudo whodid /path/to/watch
is sufficient.
.PP
.B whodid
must be run as
.B root
or with the
.B CAP_SYS_ADMIN
capability, which is required by
.BR fanotify_init (2).
.PP
.SS Operating modes
.TP
.B Modern mode (kernel \(>= 5.1)
.B whodid
calls
.BR fanotify_init (2)
with the
.B FAN_REPORT_DFID_NAME
flag, enabling directory file-identifier (FID) reporting.
This mode supports the full event set: WRITE, CREATE, DELETE, RENAME,
ATTRIB, and optionally OPEN, READ, CLOSE.
.TP
.B Basic mode (kernel < 5.1)
On older kernels the FID interface is not available.
.B whodid
falls back automatically to a plain
.B fanotify_init
session.
Only WRITE (CLOSE_WRITE) and MODIFY events are reported; CREATE, DELETE,
RENAME, and ATTRIB are not available.
A warning is printed to
.I stderr
when this fallback is active.
.SS Output format
Each event is printed to
.IR stdout :
.PP
.EX
HH:MM:SS | PID  | PROCESS                           | ACTION     | FILE
.EE
.PP
ANSI colour is applied automatically when
.I stdout
is a terminal and the
.B \-\-no\-color
flag is not set.
All path and process-name strings are stripped of C0 control characters
(including ESC / \\x1b) before output to prevent terminal escape-sequence
injection via maliciously crafted file names.
.PP
The following ACTION values may appear:
.RS
.TP
.B CREATE
File or directory created.
.TP
.B DELETE
File or directory deleted.
.TP
.B MOVE_FROM
Rename — source name.
.TP
.B MOVE_TO
Rename — destination name.
.TP
.B MODIFY
File contents changed (intermediate write).
.TP
.B WRITE
File closed after being written.
.TP
.B ATTRIB
Permissions or ownership changed.
.TP
.B OPEN
File opened (only with \fB\-a\fP).
.TP
.B READ
File read (only with \fB\-a\fP).
.TP
.B CLOSE
File closed without write (only with \fB\-a\fP).
.RE
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Show all file-system events, including OPEN, READ, and CLOSE.
By default only write-side events are shown (WRITE, MODIFY, CREATE, DELETE,
RENAME, ATTRIB).
Enabling this option significantly increases output volume on busy directories.
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-syslog
In addition to printing to
.IR stdout ,
write each event to the system journal via
.BR syslog (3)
with facility
.B LOG_DAEMON
and priority
.BR LOG_INFO .
The syslog tag is
.BR whodid .
Events can be followed with:
.EX
journalctl \-t whodid \-f
.EE
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-no\-color
Disable ANSI colour codes in the output.
Colour is also disabled automatically when
.I stdout
is not a terminal (e.g., when piping to
.BR tee (1)
or redirecting to a file).
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-self
Include file-system events generated by the
.B whodid
process itself.
By default, events whose PID matches the current
.B whodid
process are suppressed to reduce noise.
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Suppress the startup banner (the box with version, watch path, mode, and
column headers).
Useful when
.B whodid
is used as a source in shell pipelines or called from scripts where clean
output is required.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Print the version string and exit.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a usage summary to
.I stderr
and exit.
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Watch
.I /etc/
for writes, creates, and deletes:
.EX
sudo whodid /etc/
.EE
.TP
Watch
.I /var/log/
and include all open/read events:
.EX
sudo whodid \-a /var/log/
.EE
.TP
Log to a file (colour is disabled automatically):
.EX
sudo whodid /home/ | tee activity.log
.EE
.TP
Minimal pipeline-friendly output (no banner, no colour):
.EX
sudo whodid \-q \-n /tmp/
.EE
.TP
Send events to both
.I stdout
and the system journal:
.EX
sudo whodid \-\-syslog /etc/
journalctl \-t whodid \-f
.EE
.TP
Filter output to a specific process using
.BR grep (1):
.EX
sudo whodid /var/www/ | grep nginx
.EE
.TP
Watch for new cron jobs or persistence mechanisms:
.EX
sudo whodid /etc/cron.d/ &
sudo whodid /etc/systemd/system/ &
.EE
.TP
Print version and exit:
.EX
whodid \-\-version
.EE
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Monitoring ended normally (SIGINT / SIGTERM received).
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred (missing privilege, invalid path, fanotify failure).
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SIGNALS
.TP
.BR SIGINT ", " SIGTERM
Terminate monitoring gracefully.
.B whodid
prints a short summary of the total number of events seen before exiting.
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 3
Monitoring granularity is at the mount-point level.
Output is filtered in user space to the specified
.I path
prefix, but
.B fanotify_mark
watches the entire filesystem or mount containing that path.
.IP \(bu 3
Full CREATE/DELETE/RENAME/ATTRIB reporting requires Linux kernel \(>= 5.1
(Debian 11 Bullseye, Ubuntu 20.10, or later).
.IP \(bu 3
On WSL2, run
.B wsl \-\-update
from Windows PowerShell to obtain a kernel \(>= 5.1 before using
.BR whodid .
WSL1 is not supported.
.IP \(bu 3
The binary is compiled with
.BR \-fstack\-protector\-strong ,
.BR \-D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=2 ,
full RELRO
.RB ( \-Wl,\-z,relro \ \-Wl,\-z,now )
and PIE
.RB ( \-fPIE\ \-pie ).
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /proc/<pid>/exe
Symlink resolved to obtain the full executable path of the responsible process.
.TP
.I /proc/<pid>/comm
Short process name, used as fallback when
.I /proc/<pid>/exe
is no longer available (e.g., the process has already exited).
.TP
.I /proc/self/fd/<n>
Used to resolve directory file handles to absolute paths in modern mode.
.\" ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
